00:00:53,454 --> 00:00:56,255
   narrator: throughout europe  
       in the late 1700s,       

6
00:00:56,257 --> 00:01:00,526
 peaked caps were traditionally 
   worn by industrial workers.  

7
00:01:00,528 --> 00:01:02,528
      today, they are worn      
        by professionals        

8
00:01:02,530 --> 00:01:06,265
   such as security personnel,  
    members of the military,    

9
00:01:06,267 --> 00:01:09,068
      and police officials      
       that wear uniforms.      

10
00:01:13,341 --> 00:01:15,941
     in the united kingdom,     
      some police officers      

11
00:01:15,943 --> 00:01:18,744
           still wear           
  the classic custodian helmet, 

12
00:01:18,746 --> 00:01:21,347
      but now many officers     
       have chosen to wear      

13
00:01:21,349 --> 00:01:25,318
  the lightweight, comfortable, 
    and practical peaked cap.   

14
00:01:27,555 --> 00:01:30,823
       to make these caps,      
   a hat maker, or a milliner,  

15
00:01:30,825 --> 00:01:33,825
assembles a number of components
         using patterns         

16
00:01:33,827 --> 00:01:38,430
 to cut out the required pieces 
   of wool, foam, and plastic.  

17
00:01:38,432 --> 00:01:41,701
    a milliner bends a strip    
    of polypropylene plastic    

18
00:01:41,703 --> 00:01:44,236
         into a circle.         

19
00:01:44,238 --> 00:01:47,106
       she sews the joint       
  with a high-strength thread,  

20
00:01:47,108 --> 00:01:51,510
      creating the hat band     
  that will go around the head. 

21
00:01:51,512 --> 00:01:54,713
  she positions a smaller piece 
        of polypropylene,       

22
00:01:54,715 --> 00:01:58,718
   known as the badge support,  
      and sews it in place.     

23
00:01:58,720 --> 00:02:01,454
    the support will prevent    
  the weight of a police badge  

24
00:02:01,456 --> 00:02:03,889
         from distorting        
      the shape of the hat.     

25
00:02:06,393 --> 00:02:09,595
these crescent-shaped components
       are pieces of wool       

26
00:02:09,597 --> 00:02:13,132
  glued to thin, flexible foam. 

27
00:02:13,134 --> 00:02:17,136
she sews the crescents together,
   creating a circular piece,   

28
00:02:17,138 --> 00:02:19,071
   which will form the bevel.   

29
00:02:19,073 --> 00:02:22,207
     she uses a specialized,    
    long-arm sewing machine,    

30
00:02:22,209 --> 00:02:24,777
    which has been customized   
          to make hats.         

31
00:02:27,415 --> 00:02:31,483
 the seams are carefully ironed 
  flat to prevent any bulging.  

32
00:02:31,485 --> 00:02:34,686
     if the iron is too hot,    
       the foam will melt.      

33
00:02:34,688 --> 00:02:37,489
            too cool,           
   and the wool won't flatten.  

34
00:02:37,491 --> 00:02:40,826
      she aligns two strips     
       of 100% wool fabric      

35
00:02:40,828 --> 00:02:43,495
     and sews them together     
          at the ends.          

36
00:02:43,497 --> 00:02:45,897
      this piece will cover     
      the plastic stiffener     

37
00:02:45,899 --> 00:02:49,568
     forming the outer band.    

38
00:02:49,570 --> 00:02:51,770
to ensure the sizing is correct,

39
00:02:51,772 --> 00:02:54,907
  the milliner places the wool  
    cover over the stiffener.   

40
00:02:54,909 --> 00:03:00,179
                     ♪          

41
00:03:00,181 --> 00:03:01,714
   the stiffener is installed   

42
00:03:01,716 --> 00:03:05,317
           at the end           
   of the production process.   

43
00:03:05,319 --> 00:03:09,188
    next, the milliner irons    
  the seams of the band covers. 

44
00:03:11,658 --> 00:03:14,459
  she finishes the band covers  
       on a sewing machine      

45
00:03:14,461 --> 00:03:16,461
       known as a flat bed      

46
00:03:16,463 --> 00:03:19,798
       and creates a fold       
  to hold the plastic stiffener 

47
00:03:19,800 --> 00:03:22,601
  and sews the edges together.  

48
00:03:22,603 --> 00:03:26,071
  then the band cover is sewed  
          to the bevel.         

49
00:03:26,073 --> 00:03:28,741
 while it's difficult to attach 
       two pieces of cloth      

50
00:03:28,743 --> 00:03:30,209
      at different angles,      

51
00:03:30,211 --> 00:03:35,413
 this step creates an even seam 
     that runs 360 degrees.     

52
00:03:35,415 --> 00:03:37,682
  it takes at least six months  
           of training          

53
00:03:37,684 --> 00:03:39,485
   to learn how to make hats.   

54
00:03:42,223 --> 00:03:45,024
        the crown is made       
     from three materials --    

55
00:03:45,026 --> 00:03:48,627
 a combination of wool and foam,

56
00:03:48,629 --> 00:03:51,630
       a polyester lining,      

57
00:03:51,632 --> 00:03:54,266
     and a protective-grade     
          p.v.c. layer.         

58
00:03:56,437 --> 00:03:59,437
    once the three materials    
    have been sewn together,    

59
00:03:59,439 --> 00:04:03,976
       the machinist trims      
   the perimeter of the crown.  

60
00:04:03,978 --> 00:04:05,844
    she marks the side edges    

61
00:04:05,846 --> 00:04:08,514
 and aligns them with the seams 
          on the bevel.         

62
00:04:11,385 --> 00:04:13,952
     then she sews the crown    
          to the bevel.         

63
00:04:13,954 --> 00:04:17,256
    having spent a great deal   
 of time perfecting the skills, 

64
00:04:17,258 --> 00:04:19,525
          this milliner         
       makes it look easy.      

65
00:04:22,597 --> 00:04:26,132
     finally, the components    
    begin to resemble a hat.    

66
00:04:28,469 --> 00:04:31,937
 using a polypropylene template,
     the machinist positions    

67
00:04:31,939 --> 00:04:35,341
            and marks           
     two spots on the bevel.    

68
00:04:35,343 --> 00:04:39,411
she places two small brass rings
       on a special device      

69
00:04:39,413 --> 00:04:42,481
      and aligns the marks      
    with the device's posts,    

70
00:04:42,483 --> 00:04:46,485
     which cut out two holes    
       through the fabric.      

71
00:04:46,487 --> 00:04:49,955
 then she places two cup-shaped 
       rings on the posts,      

72
00:04:49,957 --> 00:04:51,891
         and the machine        
       punches them down,       

73
00:04:51,893 --> 00:04:55,493
forming eyelets for ventilation.

74
00:04:55,495 --> 00:04:57,696
              next,             
   the polypropylene stiffener  

75
00:04:57,698 --> 00:04:59,965
    is inserted into the hat.   

76
00:04:59,967 --> 00:05:05,371
     finally, the hat begins    
   to take on its final shape.  

77
00:05:05,373 --> 00:05:09,341
  the tag containing the hat's  
   size is sewed on hat band.   

78
00:05:11,379 --> 00:05:14,980
 she places a checkered-pattern 
  band on the brim of the hat,  

79
00:05:14,982 --> 00:05:19,518
          called dicing         
     or the sillitoe tartan.    

80
00:05:19,520 --> 00:05:21,786
      the milliner inserts      
         a replica badge        

81
00:05:21,788 --> 00:05:25,523
          through holes         
      in the badge support      

82
00:05:25,525 --> 00:05:28,060
   and secures it with a pin.   

83
00:05:28,062 --> 00:05:29,395
       this is a replica,       

84
00:05:29,397 --> 00:05:34,399
       since we can't show      
    real police badges on tv.   

85
00:05:34,401 --> 00:05:37,837
     next, the milliner sews    
     the peak onto the band.    

86
00:05:42,609 --> 00:05:44,276
    it took a highly skilled    
            milliner            

87
00:05:44,278 --> 00:05:47,479
     more than half an hour     
        to sew this hat.        

88
00:05:47,481 --> 00:05:49,348
they might look straightforward,

89
00:05:49,350 --> 00:05:52,351
         but peaked caps        
    are surprisingly complex.   

90
00:05:59,760 --> 00:06:05,230
                     ♪          

91
00:06:05,232 --> 00:06:09,034
            narrator:           
   a home water heater stores   
   and heats water in a tank.   

92
00:06:09,036 --> 00:06:10,569
      this is how it works.     

93
00:06:10,571 --> 00:06:12,103
   when you turn on a faucet,   

94
00:06:12,105 --> 00:06:14,840
 hot water flows out of the tank
          from the top,         

95
00:06:14,842 --> 00:06:17,976
     while cold water flows     
 into the tank from the bottom. 

96
00:06:17,978 --> 00:06:21,246
   conventional water heaters   
   are fueled by natural gas,   

97
00:06:21,248 --> 00:06:25,451
  electricity, propane, or oil. 

98
00:06:25,453 --> 00:06:28,721
   this company custom-builds   
 several types of water heaters 

99
00:06:28,723 --> 00:06:31,456
  for use with different types  
        of heat sources,        

100
00:06:31,458 --> 00:06:35,727
  such as boilers, heat pumps,  
        and solar panels.       

101
00:06:35,729 --> 00:06:38,530
    each work order includes    
       a picture outlining      

102
00:06:38,532 --> 00:06:41,333
     the pipe configuration     
   and the connecting valves,   

103
00:06:41,335 --> 00:06:46,538
    along with a list of the    
 water heater's specifications. 

104
00:06:46,540 --> 00:06:48,140
     to make a copper tank,     

105
00:06:48,142 --> 00:06:53,212
 a technician cuts a thick sheet
of copper to a specified length.

106
00:06:53,214 --> 00:06:56,615
 he aligns the end of the sheet 
  to the gradation on the table 

107
00:06:56,617 --> 00:06:59,685
       that corresponds to      
    the tank's circumference.   

108
00:06:59,687 --> 00:07:04,623
 then he actives the guillotine 
    blade with a foot pedal.    

109
00:07:04,625 --> 00:07:08,494
    a computer-guided machine   
  punches holes for the valves. 

110
00:07:08,496 --> 00:07:10,629
   this water heater requires   
           two valves           

111
00:07:10,631 --> 00:07:12,564
 at each end of the heating coil

112
00:07:12,566 --> 00:07:15,434
    and one that will connect   
   the water pipe to the tank.  

113
00:07:19,573 --> 00:07:21,707
     the technician inserts     
        the copper sheet        

114
00:07:21,709 --> 00:07:23,909
    into a mechanical roller.   

115
00:07:23,911 --> 00:07:25,644
   the rollers apply pressure,  

116
00:07:25,646 --> 00:07:28,347
        forming the sheet       
     into an open cylinder.     

117
00:07:32,519 --> 00:07:35,254
     one end of the cylinder    
    is clamped into a machine   

118
00:07:35,256 --> 00:07:37,356
    that welds linear seams.    

119
00:07:41,395 --> 00:07:43,195
     the technician inserts     
          the other end         

120
00:07:43,197 --> 00:07:45,130
         of the cylinder        
       through the machine      

121
00:07:45,132 --> 00:07:48,267
          and joins it          
    against the clamped end.    

122
00:07:48,269 --> 00:07:50,669
    the machine is programmed   
         to weld a seam         

123
00:07:50,671 --> 00:07:54,139
          to the length         
     of the connected ends.     

124
00:07:54,141 --> 00:07:56,608
     the technician monitors    
         the welding arm        

125
00:07:56,610 --> 00:08:00,211
       through a u.v. lens      
      to protect his eyes.      

126
00:08:00,213 --> 00:08:02,347
 the machine stops automatically

127
00:08:02,349 --> 00:08:06,284
         when it reaches        
   the programmed seam length.  

128
00:08:06,286 --> 00:08:08,420
this process closes the cylinder

129
00:08:08,422 --> 00:08:10,756
         with a strong,         
    pressure-resistant seam,    

130
00:08:10,758 --> 00:08:15,094
    creating the water-heater   
  tank's structural component.  

131
00:08:15,096 --> 00:08:18,563
    another technician places   
   the tank's top on a press.   

132
00:08:18,565 --> 00:08:21,633
    the press punches a hole    
  for a threaded pipe fitting.  

133
00:08:21,635 --> 00:08:24,302
  the fitting connects the pipe 
        to the hot water.       

134
00:08:24,304 --> 00:08:25,970
    using a different press,    

135
00:08:25,972 --> 00:08:27,639
      the technician makes      
          another hole          

136
00:08:27,641 --> 00:08:30,042
        into the cylinder       
     for a threaded fitting.    

137
00:08:30,044 --> 00:08:32,244
    this fitting connects to    
      an electrical element     

138
00:08:32,246 --> 00:08:35,781
        that heats water        
  in conjunction with a boiler. 

139
00:08:35,783 --> 00:08:38,516
    another technician makes    
     the tank's heating coil    

140
00:08:38,518 --> 00:08:42,454
  by running a straight copper  
   tube through three rollers.  

141
00:08:42,456 --> 00:08:44,656
the tube is bent under pressure,

142
00:08:44,658 --> 00:08:47,859
 forming it into a coiled shape.

143
00:08:47,861 --> 00:08:50,863
    the heat from the boiler,   
      pump, or solar panel      

144
00:08:50,865 --> 00:08:52,698
 flows through the heating coil,

145
00:08:52,700 --> 00:08:54,833
    heating the water stored    
          in the tank.          

146
00:08:59,406 --> 00:09:02,741
   since the copper-tube wall   
      is too thin to weld,      

147
00:09:02,743 --> 00:09:06,879
   a technician uses a fusing   
   technique known as brazing.  

148
00:09:06,881 --> 00:09:09,948
   this metal-joining process   
      brazes a flow fitting     

149
00:09:09,950 --> 00:09:11,616
 on one end of the heating coil 

150
00:09:11,618 --> 00:09:13,752
      and a return fitting      
          on the other.         

151
00:09:16,557 --> 00:09:20,291
     next, the heating coil     
     is placed in the tank.     

152
00:09:20,293 --> 00:09:24,096
  the fittings protrude through 
  a hole at the top and bottom. 

153
00:09:24,098 --> 00:09:26,831
 the technician secures each one
           with a nut,          

154
00:09:26,833 --> 00:09:29,568
     then tightens the nuts     
     with an impact wrench.     

155
00:09:31,572 --> 00:09:35,574
  like the dome top, the bottom 
 component's edges are grooved, 

156
00:09:35,576 --> 00:09:37,509
        allowing the tank       
        to fit perfectly        

157
00:09:37,511 --> 00:09:39,311
     into the cylinder base.    

158
00:09:42,650 --> 00:09:45,650
     once the top and bottom    
    components are installed,   

159
00:09:45,652 --> 00:09:47,785
       the tank goes back       
     to the brazing station     

160
00:09:47,787 --> 00:09:49,455
       for final assembly.      

161
00:09:52,392 --> 00:09:54,993
         a welder brazes        
  the top and bottom components 

162
00:09:54,995 --> 00:09:56,395
        to the cylinder,        

163
00:09:56,397 --> 00:09:58,797
         then he brazes         
    a feed fitting to a hole    

164
00:09:58,799 --> 00:10:00,598
  near the bottom of the tank.  

165
00:10:00,600 --> 00:10:03,068
     this location is where     
        cold water enters       

166
00:10:03,070 --> 00:10:04,703
     the tank to be heated.     

167
00:10:08,409 --> 00:10:12,344
   next, a technician conducts  
     a quality-control test.    

168
00:10:12,346 --> 00:10:16,148
  he blocks the three fittings, 
  fills the cylinder with air,  

169
00:10:16,150 --> 00:10:19,551
then submerges the tank in water
    to check for air bubbles,   

170
00:10:19,553 --> 00:10:21,353
  which would indicate a leak.  

171
00:10:21,355 --> 00:10:27,492
                     ♪          

172
00:10:27,494 --> 00:10:29,895
 a stainless-steel water heater 
         is constructed         

173
00:10:29,897 --> 00:10:31,363
   just like a copper heater,   

174
00:10:31,365 --> 00:10:33,799
 except that they don't require 
          any brazing.          

175
00:10:37,371 --> 00:10:41,239
  a robot sprays the tanks with 
  expandable polyurethane foam  

176
00:10:41,241 --> 00:10:43,041
         for insulation.        

177
00:10:43,043 --> 00:10:45,577
      the customer selects      
    the degree of insulation,   

178
00:10:45,579 --> 00:10:49,314
    one to four inches thick.   

179
00:10:49,316 --> 00:10:53,518
the foam takes just five minutes
            to cure.            

180
00:10:53,520 --> 00:10:56,922
  as the tank stores hot water, 
     the insulation reduces     

181
00:10:56,924 --> 00:11:00,025
       the amount of heat       
    the tank loses over time.   

182
00:11:08,535 --> 00:11:13,871
                     ♪          

183
00:11:13,873 --> 00:11:15,407
            narrator:           
  electrically powered vehicles 

184
00:11:15,409 --> 00:11:18,477
          may seem like         
   a 21st-century phenomenon,   

185
00:11:18,479 --> 00:11:21,680
     but they were actually     
  first invented in the 1880s.  

186
00:11:21,682 --> 00:11:24,082
        during that time,       
     they were very popular,    

187
00:11:24,084 --> 00:11:27,619
until combustion-engine vehicles
     became the new normal.     

188
00:11:27,621 --> 00:11:29,554
             today,             
   these electrically powered   

189
00:11:29,556 --> 00:11:34,359
    alternative-fuel vehicles   
     are making a comeback.     

190
00:11:34,361 --> 00:11:38,296
   this manufacturer produces   
 a wide range of electric boats.

191
00:11:38,298 --> 00:11:41,166
  thanks to powerful batteries, 
     some of these vehicles     

192
00:11:41,168 --> 00:11:45,637
           can travel           
     over 35 miles per hour.    

193
00:11:45,639 --> 00:11:48,973
       craftspeople apply       
   a gel-coat skin to a mold,   

194
00:11:48,975 --> 00:11:51,310
         using a product        
       derived from vinyl.      

195
00:11:53,447 --> 00:11:56,447
       then they layer on       
     a dry fiberglass fabric    

196
00:11:56,449 --> 00:12:00,319
         and vacuum-bag         
      the entire assembly.      

197
00:12:00,321 --> 00:12:03,155
       the vacuum suction       
     draws in liquid resin,     

198
00:12:03,157 --> 00:12:05,457
     infusing the material.     

199
00:12:05,459 --> 00:12:08,393
  a craftsman marks a dry spot  
         as a test point        

200
00:12:08,395 --> 00:12:11,463
      to monitor and ensure     
      complete saturation.      

201
00:12:14,401 --> 00:12:17,536
      the infusion process      
     takes about two hours.     

202
00:12:17,538 --> 00:12:21,473
   once complete, the assembly  
will cure for four to six hours,

203
00:12:21,475 --> 00:12:25,143
    depending on the general    
humidity and temperature levels.

204
00:12:25,145 --> 00:12:28,880
    once cured, the assembly    
    is removed from the mold.   

205
00:12:28,882 --> 00:12:31,082
     despite the structure's    
          light weight,         

206
00:12:31,084 --> 00:12:35,220
     this deck is incredibly    
   strong, rigid, and durable.  

207
00:12:38,225 --> 00:12:42,628
 the fiberglass decks and hulls 
   make up the boat's shells.   

208
00:12:44,965 --> 00:12:48,233
      a craftswoman applies     
   a high-strength marine glue  

209
00:12:48,235 --> 00:12:52,170
 to a recessed area of the deck.

210
00:12:52,172 --> 00:12:55,707
    she installs an anti-skid   
         deck insertion.        

211
00:12:55,709 --> 00:13:01,113
  this material is a composite  
   designed to resemble wood.   

212
00:13:01,115 --> 00:13:03,782
        unlike real wood,       
     this composite material    

213
00:13:03,784 --> 00:13:06,051
     will last the lifetime     
           of the boat          

214
00:13:06,053 --> 00:13:10,589
        and won't require       
   any additional maintenance.  

215
00:13:10,591 --> 00:13:14,392
  the craftswoman uses a roller 
    to apply pressure evenly    

216
00:13:14,394 --> 00:13:16,594
        across the entire       
        decking surface.        

217
00:13:16,596 --> 00:13:20,398
    this step will eliminate    
    any unwanted air pockets.   

218
00:13:20,400 --> 00:13:22,868
      next, a mirror-image      
         decking section        

219
00:13:22,870 --> 00:13:25,670
  is applied to the other side. 

220
00:13:25,672 --> 00:13:29,341
      a specialist installs     
 the electrical-wiring harness. 

221
00:13:29,343 --> 00:13:32,477
       to avoid corrosion,      
  marine-grade wiring is stored 

222
00:13:32,479 --> 00:13:34,713
     in a sealed environment    
         under the deck.        

223
00:13:38,485 --> 00:13:40,419
        since the decking       
         is lightweight,        

224
00:13:40,421 --> 00:13:44,056
it only takes two people to lift
   and install it on the hull.  

225
00:13:46,226 --> 00:13:49,127
       the lip of the deck      
     fits snugly into place.    

226
00:13:52,299 --> 00:13:57,168
  the most powerful boat models 
 require lithium-ion batteries. 

